f 5 years of continuous service (as per Payment of Gratuity Act) | Not explicitly mentioned |\n| Policy Review | This Payroll Policy will be reviewed annually or as necessitated by changes in applicable tax laws, labour regulations, statutory requirements, or organisational restructuring. | We have established an [annual] revision of our handbook to bring it up to date with legislation and employment trends. |\n\n### Key Insights\n\n- **Differences:**\n  1. **Attendance and Leave Management**: Payroll policy integrates attendance and leave management, while leave policy focuses on sick leave and other types of leave.\n  2. **LOP and Leave Encashment**: Payroll policy outlines circumstances for Loss of Pay (LOP) and leave encashment, while leave policy does not explicitly mention these aspects.\n  3. **Record Keeping**: Payroll policy specifies record-keeping requirements, while leave policy does not.\n- **Similarity:**\n  1. **Annual Review**: Both policies are reviewed annually or as necessitated by changes in applicable laws or regulations.	2026-04-10 14:51:17.14898
acd471bc-370c-42a9-aa5e-18761397cbdc	5f9edd8b-1a51-47a3-91b3-76d305f4b287	54	explain dress code at artemis?	**Dress Code at Artemis**\n\nAt Artemis, the dress code is Business Casual. This means that employees are expected to dress in a professional and respectful manner, but with a more relaxed tone than a traditional business dress code.\n\n**Key Guidelines:**\n\n1. **Business Casual**: Employees are expected to dress in a way that is professional, yet relaxed. This can include dress pants or skirts, blouses or button-down shirts, and loafers or dress shoes.\n2. **No Workout Clothes**: Employees are expected to avoid wearing workout clothes, such as yoga pants or t-shirts, to work.\n3. **No Unprofessional Attire**: Employees are expected to avoid wearing clothing that is unprofessional, such as ripped jeans, tank tops, or flip-flops.\n4. **Respect for Diversity**: Artemis respects and permits grooming styles, clothing, and accessories that are dictated by religious beliefs, ethnicity, or disability.\n\n**Additional Guidelines:**\n\n1. **Client Meetings**: Employees are expected to dress more formally for client meetings, such as in a suit and tie or a professional dress.\n2. **Company Events**: Employees are expected to dress according to the dress code specified for the event.\n\nOverall, the dress code at Artemis is designed to promote a professional and respectful work environment, while also allowing employees to express their personal style.	2026-04-10 14:58:17.253465
