ab4abe91-1a42-4389-bc76-900820f8f725	111a6a4b-5853-4593-a68c-9b67527a18d7	1	leave policy	Based on the provided policy excerpts, here are the relevant rules regarding leave policy:\n\n* If you are absent for more than three days of sick leave, you may need to provide a doctor's note and/or complete a sick leave form for insurance purposes. (Document: artemis_employee_handbook.pdf, Page: None)\n* Eligible employees have access to an insurance package. For more information, contact HR. (Document: artemis_employee_handbook.pdf, Page: None)\n* According to the Consolidated Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act (COBRA), eligible employees may choose to continue their group health benefits for a limited period after leaving the company due to a qualifying event, such as termination for reasons other than gross misconduct and reduction in hours of employment. (Document: artemis_employee_handbook.pdf, Page: None)	2026-04-16 04:29:41.659835
af45680a-77b5-406a-9654-c5f887b7ec0d	0654d35e-d48f-4895-9c53-57c8d2cd84d9	2	summairze the resignation policy	**Resignation Policy Summary**\n\n**Document:** artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n**Key Points:**\n\n1. **Definition of Resignation:** You resign when you voluntarily inform HR or your manager that you will stop working for the company. We also consider you resigned if you don’t come to work for three consecutive days without notice.\n2. **Notice Period:** You are not obliged to give advance notice before resigning, but we ask that you give at least two weeks' notice, if possible. If you hold a highly specialized or executive position, we ask that you give us at least a month's notice, when possible.\n3. **Acceptance of Resignation:** We accept verbal resignations, but we prefer that you submit a written and signed notice of resignation for our HR records.\n4. **Tuition or Relocation Reimbursement:** If you have relocated or studied at our company's expense, you are bound by your contract to remain with us for at least two years. If you resign before that period, you may have to reimburse us for part or all of these expenses.\n5. **Forced Resignation:** Forcing someone into resignation (directly or indirectly) is constructive dismissal and we won’t tolerate it. We prohibit employees from creating a hostile or unpleasant environment, demanding or coaxing an employee to resign, victimizing, harassing or retaliating against an employee, or forcing an employee to resign by taking unofficial adverse actions.\n\n**Main Rules:**\n\n1. Provide at least two weeks' notice before resigning, if possible.\n2. Submit a written and signed notice of resignation for our HR records.\n3. Do not force someone into resignation.\n4. Reimburse the company for tuition or relocation expenses if you resign before the agreed period.\n\n**Critical Information:**\n\n1. We will reply with an acceptance of resignation letter within two days.\n2. HR will inform your manager that you are resigning if you haven’t already done so.\n3. Whether you want to announce your resignation to your team is up to you, but we encourage you to be open.\n\nSources:\n- artemis_employee_handbook.pdf	2026-04-16 10:04:26.414145
7bae882c-664e-42b0-9379-4a056c0efda2	111a6a4b-5853-4593-a68c-9b67527a18d7	2	leave policy	**Leave Policy Summary**\n\n**Document:** artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n**Key Points:**\n\n* **Eligible Employees:** Eligible employees can continue their group health benefits for a limited period after leaving the company under the Consolidated Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act (COBRA).\n* **Sick Leave:**\n\t+ Inform manager and send a sick leave request through HRIS.\n\t+ Take a partial day off or work from home, but rest and recuperate for a day before returning to work.\n\t+ Use PTO or arrange for a flexible work schedule for routine health care appointments.\n\t+ Submit a physician's note or other medical certification and/or complete a sick leave form for insurance purposes if absent for more than 3 days.\n* **Long-term Illness:**\n\t+ The U.S. Family and Medical Leave Act provides 12 weeks of unpaid, job-protected leave for medical and family reasons.\n\t+ Eligible employees have worked for more than 12 months and 1,250 hours within 12 months before the leave begins.\n* **Bereavement Leave:**\n\t+ 3 days of paid bereavement leave to arrange a funeral or memorial service, attend a funeral or memorial service, resolve matters of inheritance, fulfill other family obligations, or mourn.\n\t+ 2 additional unpaid days off if traveling long-distance for a funeral or service.\n* **Jury Duty and Voting:**\n\t+ Exempt employees can take 1 day of unpaid leave extension of up to 2 months for jury duty.\n\t+ Contact HR as soon as possible to arrange this.\n* **Parental Leave:**\n\t+ Eligible employees can take up to 12 weeks of unpaid, job-protected leave for medical and family reasons, including recovery from a serious health condition or caring for an immediate family member.\n\t+ Eligible employees have worked for more than 12 months and 1,250 hours within 12 months before the leave begins.\n\t+ Returning to work after parental leave, the company offers remote working, flexible hours, onsite/external paid day care, and lactation rooms.\n* **Resignation:**\n\t+ Resignation occurs when an employee voluntarily informs HR or their manager that they will stop working for the company.\n\t+ No advance notice is required, but it is recommended for efficiency's sake.\n\t+ Resigned employees may ask for references, and their manager has the right to oblige or refuse.\n\n**Main Rules:**\n\n* Eligible employees can continue their group health benefits under COBRA.\n* Sick leave requires informing the manager and sending a sick leave request through HRIS.\n* Long-term illness requires 12 weeks of unpaid, job-protected leave under the U.S. Family and Medical Leave Act.\n* Bereavement leave provides 3 days of paid leave and 2 additional unpaid days off for traveling long-distance.\n* Jury duty and voting leave require contacting HR to arrange the leave.\n* Parental leave provides up to 12 weeks of unpaid, job-protected leave for medical and family reasons.\n* Resignation requires informing HR or the manager that the employee will stop working for the company.\n\n**Critical Information:**\n\n* Eligible employees must have worked for more than 12 months and 1,250 hours within 12 months before taking long-term illness or parental leave.\n* Resigned employees may ask for references, but their manager has the right to oblige or refuse.\n\nSources:\n- artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n**Other questions you would like to know about**\n- Would you like to know more about Progressive Discipline Process?\n- Would you like to know more about Family and Medical Leave Act?\n- Would you like to know more about Jury Duty Leave Policy?	2026-04-16 10:00:07.27549
c4745956-49af-4624-b8db-1a5068231fe9	111a6a4b-5853-4593-a68c-9b67527a18d7	3	payroll policy	**Payroll Policy Summary**\n\n**Source:** artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n**Key Points:**\n\n1. **Pay Frequency:** Payroll is paid at the end of every month by bank transfers.\n2. **Pay Calculation:** Hourly employees should be diligent in clocking in and out to ensure accurate pay calculation.\n3. **Holiday Pay:**\n\t* Exempt employees receive their normal compensation without any deductions.\n\t* Permanent non-exempt employees receive holiday pay as a benefit after working for more than three months.\n4. **Working on Holidays:**\n\t* Non-exempt employees receive their regular hourly rate with a premium for working on a holiday.\n\t* Exempt employees receive an additional day of PTO that must be taken within 12 months after the holiday.\n5. **Overtime Pay:** Hours worked on a holiday are counted to determine entitlement to overtime pay.\n6. **PTO (Paid Time Off):**\n\t* Employees receive 20 days of PTO per year.\n\t* PTO accrual begins on the day of employment and increases by 1.7 days per month.\n\t* Employees can take PTO at any time after the first week of employment.\n7. **Sick Leave:**\n\t* Employees receive one week of paid sick leave.\n\t* In states or countries with more generous sick leave laws, the company will follow those laws.\n\n**Main Rules:**\n\n1. Hourly employees must clock in and out accurately to ensure proper pay calculation.\n2. Non-exempt employees must be informed at least three days in advance if they are required to work on a holiday.\n3. Exempt employees must take an additional day of PTO within 12 months after working on a holiday.\n4. Employees must follow the company's PTO and sick leave policies to ensure proper compensation and benefits.\n\nSources:\n- artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n**Other questions you would like to know about**\n- Would you like to know more about Paid Time Off (PTO) policy?\n- Would you like to know more about Overtime policy?\n- Would you like to know more about Sick Leave policy?	2026-04-16 10:00:48.41524
d7375f8d-7ff6-48af-a06d-9745656dcf61	111a6a4b-5853-4593-a68c-9b67527a18d7	4	culture and dress code	**Comparison of Culture and Dress Code Policies**\n\n**Policy Documents:** artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n**Comparison Focus:** Culture and Dress Code\n\n**Similarities:**\n\n| Policy | Culture | Dress Code |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Mutual Respect | Our workplace is founded on mutual respect and we won’t allow anyone to compromise this foundation. |  |\n| Professionalism | We want to ensure that relationships between employees are appropriate and harmonious. We outline our guidelines and we ask you to always behave professionally. |  |\n| Cleanliness | We expect you to be clean when coming to work and avoid wearing clothes that are unprofessional (e.g. workout clothes.) |  |\n\n**Differences:**\n\n| Policy | Culture | Dress Code |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Work Environment | At Artemis, the way we work matters as much as the outcomes we deliver. Teams are encouraged to ask questions, challenge assumptions, and take ownership of their contributions. | Our company’s official dress code is Business Casual. However, an employee’s position may also inform how they should dress. |\n| Communication | There is a strong emphasis on clarity—both in communication and in thinking. Whether drafting a report or leading a client discussion, employees are expected to make their ideas understandable and actionable. | As long as you conform with our guidelines above, we don’t have specific expectations about what types of clothes or accessories you should wear. |\n| Adaptability | Collaboration is deliberate rather than automatic; people are expected to bring their perspective, but also to adapt when better ideas emerge. |  |\n| Recognition | Good work is recognized through impact rather than visibility. |  |\n| Formality | If you frequently meet with clients or prospects, conform to a more formal dress code. |  |\n| Accommodations | We respect and permit grooming styles, clothing and accessories that are dictated by religious beliefs, ethnicity or disability. |  |\n| Social Media | If you handle our social media accounts or speak on our company’s behalf, we expect you to protect our company’s image and reputation. |  |\n\n**Key Takeaways:**\n\n* Artemis values a culture of mutual respect, professionalism, and cleanliness.\n* The dress code is Business Casual, but employees are expected to adapt to more formal dress codes when meeting with clients or prospects.\n* Employees are encouraged to be adaptable, communicate clearly, and recognize good work through impact rather than visibility.\n* The company respects and accommodates employees with different grooming styles, clothing, and accessories due to religious beliefs, ethnicity, or disability.\n\nSources:\n- artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n**Other questions you would like to know about**\n- Would you like to know more about Workplace Visitors?\n- Would you like to know more about Fraternization?\n- Would you like to know more about Workplace Safety and Health?	2026-04-16 10:01:42.353565
9879a0eb-fedd-49d6-8bb7-8bce004eeb75	111a6a4b-5853-4593-a68c-9b67527a18d7	5	culture	Based on the provided policy excerpts, here are the relevant rules related to culture:\n\n* At Artemis, the way we work matters as much as the outcomes we deliver. Teams are encouraged to ask questions, challenge assumptions, and take ownership of their contributions. (Artemis Employee Handbook, Our Culture)\n* Collaboration is deliberate rather than automatic; people are expected to bring their perspective, but also to adapt when better ideas emerge. (Artemis Employee Handbook, Our Culture)\n* There is a strong emphasis on clarity—both in communication and in thinking. Whether drafting a report or leading a client discussion, employees are expected to make their ideas understandable and actionable. (Artemis Employee Handbook, Our Culture)\n* Titles matter less than accountability, and good work is recognized through impact rather than visibility. (Artemis Employee Handbook, Our Culture)	2026-04-16 04:32:47.248315
