c25f3f69-015d-4d32-8a35-42dc72966b45	94986a10-33ea-433f-926a-1c8fe1583385	3	summarize culture at artemis	**Summary of Culture at Artemis**\n\n**Our Culture**\n\n* The way we work matters as much as the outcomes we deliver.\n* Teams are encouraged to ask questions, challenge assumptions, and take ownership of their contributions.\n* Collaboration is deliberate rather than automatic; people are expected to bring their perspective, but also to adapt when better ideas emerge.\n* There is a strong emphasis on clarity—both in communication and in thinking.\n* Titles matter less than accountability, and good work is recognized through impact rather than visibility.\n\n**Our Vision**\n\n* Our mission is to unlock organizational potential through tailored strategic insights and dependable client support.\n* We see Artemis as a long-term partner to our clients, not just a service provider.\n\n**Employee Relationships**\n\n* We want to ensure that relationships between employees are appropriate and harmonious.\n* We outline our guidelines and ask employees to always behave professionally.\n* Fraternization refers to dating or being friends with your colleagues.\n* Non-consensual romantic relationships are not allowed.\n* Friendships at work are encouraged, but personal disputes should be kept outside of the workplace.\n\n**Employment of Relatives**\n\n* We would not like to see phenomena of nepotism, favoritism or conflicts of interest, so we will place some restrictions on hiring employees' relatives.\n\n**Employee Training and Development**\n\n* We invest in our employees' professional development to show our gratitude for their hard work.\n* Each employee has $1,000 annually to spend on educational activities or material.\n* We offer online courses and other training opportunities to help employees improve their efficiency and productivity.\n\n**Benefits and Perks**\n\n* We provide information on our health insurance plans and benefits like work from home options and company-issued equipment.\n* Employee health is important to us, and we don't discriminate against people with disabilities or health conditions.\n\n**Employee Acknowledgement**\n\n* Please sign to acknowledge that you've read this handbook and that you are committed to following our policies.\n* If you need any clarifications, feel free to ask HR.\n\nSources:\n- artemis_employee_handbook.pdf	2026-04-16 12:21:14.363919
4a75bf3a-6cea-452a-ba3a-0ff966018bc8	94986a10-33ea-433f-926a-1c8fe1583385	4	paid leaves and sick leaves 	**Comparison of Paid Leaves and Sick Leaves**\n\n**Policy Documents:** artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n**Comparison Focus:** Paid Leaves and Sick Leaves\n\n**Similarities:**\n\n| Feature | Paid Leaves | Sick Leaves |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Eligibility | All employees | All employees |\n| Purpose | To provide time off for various reasons | To provide time off for short-term illness, injuries, mental issues, and other indisposition |\n| Request Process | Employees can request PTO through HRIS | Employees can request sick leave through HRIS |\n| Accrual | Employees can accrue PTO | Employees can accrue paid sick leave |\n| Transfer | Employees can transfer remaining PTO to the next year | Employees can transfer remaining sick leave to the next year |\n| Compensation | Employees may receive compensation for accrued PTO upon termination | Employees may receive compensation for accrued sick leave upon termination |\n\n**Differences:**\n\n| Feature | Paid Leaves | Sick Leaves |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Duration | Varies (e.g., parental leave, bereavement leave) | One week (or more, depending on local law) |\n| Pay | Varies (e.g., exempt employees receive normal compensation, non-exempt employees receive holiday pay) | Paid |\n| Notice Period | Varies (e.g., parental leave requires a month's notice) | No specific notice period mentioned |\n| Use of PTO | Employees can use PTO for routine health care appointments | Employees should use PTO or arrange for a flexible work schedule for routine health care appointments |\n| Medical Certification | Employees may be asked to submit a physician's note or other medical certification for sick leave | Employees may be asked to submit a physician's note or other medical certification for sick leave |\n| Long-term Illness | The U.S. Family and Medical Leave Act provides 12 weeks of unpaid, job-protected leave | Long-term illness is not explicitly mentioned in the policy |\n\n**Key Differences:**\n\n* Paid leaves have varying durations and pay structures, while sick leaves have a standard duration and pay.\n* Paid leaves often require a notice period, while sick leaves do not.\n* Employees can use PTO for routine health care appointments, but sick leaves are specifically mentioned for short-term illness, injuries, mental issues, and other indisposition.\n\nSources:\n- artemis_employee_handbook.pdf	2026-04-16 12:21:29.514445
1c15556b-9c10-42fa-b6b2-d78e3da81c9e	bdd02ecd-e643-4a14-95ab-316eca0f0644	8	compare the sick leave and paid time off policy	**Comparison of Sick Leave and Paid Time Off (PTO) Policies**\n\n**Policy Documents:** artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n**Comparison Focus:** Sick Leave and Paid Time Off (PTO) Policies\n\n**Similarities:**\n\n| Policy | Sick Leave | PTO |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Accrual | Begins on the day of joining the company | Begins on the day of joining the company |\n| Accrual Rate | Not specified | 1.7 days per month |\n| Maximum Accrual | Not specified | 25 days overall |\n| Use of Accrued Time | Can be used at any time after the first week with the company | Can be used at any time after the first week with the company |\n| Carryover | Can be transferred to the next year | Can be transferred to the next year |\n\n**Differences:**\n\n| Policy | Sick Leave | PTO |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Number of Days | 1 week (or more in states/countries with greater entitlement) | 20 days per year (with a cap of 25 days overall) |\n| Purpose | To recover from short-term illness, injuries, mental issues, and other indisposition | For vacation, personal, or family reasons |\n| Request Process | Send a sick leave request through HRIS | Send a PTO request through HRIS |\n| Manager Approval | Required | Required |\n| Use of PTO for Sick Leave | Can use PTO for sick leave, but advised to use sick leave for contagious diseases | Can use PTO for sick leave, but advised to use sick leave for contagious diseases |\n| Physician's Note | May be required for absences of more than 3 days | Not specified |\n| Carryover of Unused Time | Can be transferred to the next year | Can be transferred to the next year |\n\n**Additional Notes:**\n\n* The company offers a floating day, which can be taken as a holiday on any day chosen.\n* Exempt employees receive their normal compensation without any deductions on holidays, while non-exempt employees receive their regular hourly rate with a premium for working on a holiday.\n* The company will count hours worked on a holiday to decide whether an employee is entitled to overtime pay.\n\nSources:\n- artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n### Other questions you would like to know about\n- Would you like to know more about Overtime Pay Policy?\n- Would you like to know more about Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA) Policy?\n- Would you like to know more about Termination Policy?	2026-04-16 12:21:34.303373
dec3b41b-b8cd-41bb-b1ff-516f49868182	bdd02ecd-e643-4a14-95ab-316eca0f0644	9	summarize the resignation procedure	**Resignation Procedure Summary**\n\n**Document:** artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n**Key Points:**\n\n* **Definition of Resignation:** You resign when you voluntarily inform HR or your manager that you will stop working for our company. We also consider you resigned if you don’t come to work for three consecutive days without notice.\n* **Notice Period:** You are not obliged to give us advance notice before resigning, but we ask that you give at least two weeks' notice, if possible. If you hold a highly specialized or executive position, we ask that you give us at least a month's notice, when possible.\n* **Acceptance of Resignation:** We accept verbal resignations, but we prefer that you submit a written and signed notice of resignation for our HR records.\n* **Formalities:** We will reply with an acceptance of resignation letter within two days. HR will inform your manager that you are resigning if you haven’t already done so.\n* **Tuition or Relocation Reimbursement:** If you have relocated or studied at our company’s expense, you are bound by your contract to remain with us for at least two years. If you resign before that period, you may have to reimburse us for part or all of these expenses.\n\n**Critical Information:**\n\n* Forcing someone into resignation is considered constructive dismissal and is not tolerated.\n* You can resign anytime at your own free will and nobody should force you into resignation.\n* If you resign, you may ask for references, and your manager has a right to oblige or refuse.\n\nSources:\n- artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n### Other questions you would like to know about\n- Would you like to know more about Progressive Discipline Process?\n- Would you like to know more about Severance Pay?\n- Would you like to know more about Forced Resignation?	2026-04-16 12:22:56.33376
