c73acd0e-e3dd-42e9-bab3-31fc2ed658ab	e361045b-5b10-4695-944a-a47e8cb33ed2	4	compare sick leave and PTO	**Comparison of Sick Leave and PTO Policies**\n\n**Policy Documents:** artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n**Comparison Focus:** Sick Leave and PTO\n\n**Similarities:**\n\n| Feature | Sick Leave | PTO |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Accrual | Begins on the day of employment | Begins on the day of employment |\n| Use | Can be taken at any time after the first week of employment | Can be taken at any time after the first week of employment |\n| Transfer | Remaining days can be transferred to the next year | Remaining days can be transferred to the next year |\n| Compensation | May be compensated with the final paycheck according to local law | May be compensated with the final paycheck according to local law |\n\n**Differences:**\n\n| Feature | Sick Leave | PTO |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Duration | One week of paid sick leave | Up to 25 days of paid time off |\n| Eligibility | Available for short-term illness, injuries, mental issues, and other indisposition | Available for any reason |\n| Request Process | Must be requested through HRIS | Must be requested through HRIS |\n| Approval | Manager or HR approval required | Manager or HR approval required |\n| Use of PTO for Sick Leave | Can use PTO for routine health care appointments | Can use PTO for any reason |\n| Physician's Note | May be required for absences of more than three days | Not mentioned |\n| Long-term Illness | Eligible for up to 12 weeks of unpaid, job-protected leave under the US Family and Medical Leave Act | Not mentioned |\n\n**Key Differences:**\n\n* Sick leave is specifically for short-term illness, injuries, mental issues, and other indisposition, while PTO can be used for any reason.\n* Sick leave has a shorter duration of one week, while PTO has a maximum duration of 25 days.\n* The request process and approval requirements are the same for both sick leave and PTO.\n* PTO can be used for routine health care appointments, while sick leave is specifically for short-term illness and injuries.\n* A physician's note may be required for absences of more than three days for sick leave, but not mentioned for PTO.\n* Long-term illness is eligible for up to 12 weeks of unpaid, job-protected leave under the US Family and Medical Leave Act, but not mentioned for PTO.\n\nSources:\n- artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\n\n### Other questions you would like to know about\n- Would you like to know more about Overtime Pay?\n- Would you like to know more about Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA)?\n- Would you like to know more about Workers' Compensation?	2026-04-16 12:47:34.773294
