47537255-cdfe-47b6-bea3-5c9fbc6d2c50	c110cd68-5939-4125-9201-936d8a419afd	summarization_tool	{"query": "culture", "user_role": "Employee"}	{"answer": "**Artemis Employee Handbook: Culture**\\n\\n**Summary:**\\n\\nThe Artemis Employee Handbook outlines the company's culture, values, and expectations for employees. The following are the key points related to the user's request:\\n\\n### Our Culture\\n\\n* The way we work matters as much as the outcomes we deliver.\\n* Teams are encouraged to ask questions, challenge assumptions, and take ownership of their contributions.\\n* Collaboration is deliberate rather than automatic; people are expected to bring their perspective, but also to adapt when better ideas emerge.\\n* There is a strong emphasis on clarity—both in communication and in thinking.\\n* Titles matter less than accountability, and good work is recognized through impact rather than visibility.\\n\\n### Our Vision\\n\\n* Our mission is to unlock organizational potential through tailored strategic insights and dependable client support.\\n* We see Artemis as a long-term partner to our clients, not just a service provider.\\n\\n### Equal Opportunity Employment\\n\\n* Artemis is an equal opportunity employer and does not tolerate discrimination against protected characteristics (gender, age, sexual orientation, race, nationality, ethnicity, religion, disability, veteran status).\\n* We want all employees (including executives and HR) to treat others with respect and professionalism.\\n\\n### Harassment and Violence\\n\\n* To build a happy and productive workplace, we need everyone to treat others well and help them feel safe.\\n* Each of us should do our part to prevent harassment and workplace violence.\\n\\n### Employee Relationships\\n\\n* We want to ensure that relationships between employees are appropriate and harmonious.\\n* We outline our guidelines and ask you to always behave professionally.\\n\\n### Fraternization\\n\\n* Fraternization refers to dating or being friends with your colleagues.\\n* Dating colleagues: maintain professionalism and keep personal discussions outside of the workplace.\\n* Dating managers: supervisors must not date their direct reports.\\n* Friendships at work: employees who work together may naturally form friendships, but we expect you to focus on your work and keep personal disputes outside of the workplace.\\n\\n### Employment of Relatives\\n\\n* Everyone in our company should be hired, recognized, or promoted because of their skills, character, and work ethic.\\n* We would not like to see phenomena of nepotism, favoritism, or conflicts of interest, so we will place some restrictions on hiring employees' relatives.\\n\\n### Solicitation and Distribution\\n\\n* Solicitation is any form of requesting money, support, or participation for products, groups, organizations, or causes which are unrelated to our company.\\n* Distribution means disseminating literature or material for commercial or political purposes.\\n* We don't allow solicitation and distribution by non-employees in our workplace.\\n\\n### Compensation & Development\\n\\n* In this section, we outline our guidelines for compensating employees according to their employment status.\\n* We also describe our performance management and employee development policies.\\n\\n**Policy Document:** artemis_employee_handbook.pdf", "chunks_count": 20, "sources_count": 1}	2026-04-16 15:45:53.025208
12cfeda4-2140-4d9d-b590-c46eed0269b9	e9df2ef2-7bb6-4049-8e14-30d0cf048f15	summarization_tool	{"query": "what is leave policy", "user_role": "Employee"}	{"answer": "**Leave Policy Summary**\\n\\n**Document:** artemis_employee_handbook.pdf\\n\\n**Key Points:**\\n\\n* **Sick Leave:**\\n\\t+ Inform manager and send a sick leave request through HRIS if you become sick.\\n\\t+ Take a partial day off or work from home, but rest and recuperate for a day before returning to work.\\n\\t+ Use PTO or arrange for a flexible work schedule for routine health care appointments.\\n\\t+ Submit a physician's note or other medical certification and/or complete a sick leave form for absences over three days.\\n* **Long-term Illness (Family and Medical Leave Act):**\\n\\t+ 12 weeks of unpaid, job-protected leave in a 12-month period for medical and family reasons.\\n\\t+ Eligible for leave if you have worked for over 12 months and 1,250 hours within 12 months before leave begins.\\n* **Bereavement Leave:**\\n\\t+ Up to two months of unpaid leave extension for bereavement.\\n\\t+ Contact HR as soon as possible to arrange this.\\n* **Parental Leave:**\\n\\t+ Eligible for leave if you have worked for over 12 months and 1,250 hours within 12 months before leave begins.\\n\\t+ Three months' notice before leave begins is recommended.\\n\\t+ Up to two months of unpaid leave extension for complications during childbirth or other issues.\\n* **PTO (Paid Time Off):**\\n\\t+ You can transfer any remaining PTO to the next year.\\n\\t+ We encourage you to use your time off throughout the year.\\n\\t+ Accrued PTO may be compensated with your final paycheck according to local law.\\n\\n**Main Rules:**\\n\\n* Provide advance notice for resignation, ideally two weeks or a month for highly specialized or executive positions.\\n* Submit a written and signed resignation letter.\\n* You are not obliged to give advance notice before resigning, but it is recommended for efficiency's sake.\\n\\n**Critical Information:**\\n\\n* If you are laid off, you may receive references from your manager.\\n* If you resign, you may ask for references, and your manager has the right to oblige or refuse.", "chunks_count": 20, "sources_count": 1}	2026-04-16 15:48:01.404451
