301d1706-48af-45ce-a423-7e445112aa80	c5cac33e-d683-42e5-a870-f56bd795e9d7	95	may have to reimburse us for part or all of these expenses. \n \nForced resignation \nYou can resign anytime at your own free will and nobody should force you into \nresignation. Forcing someone into resigning (directly or indirectly) is constructive \ndismissal and we won’t tolerate it. Specifically, we prohibit employees from: \n■ Creating a hostile or unpleasant environment. \n■ Demanding or coaxing an employee to resign. \n■ Victimizing, harassing or retaliating against an employee. \n■ Forcing an employee to resign by taking unofficial adverse actions (e.g. \ndemotions, increased workload). \n \nTermination \nTerminating an employee is always unpleasant but sometimes necessary. If that \nhappens, we want to ensure we act lawfully and respectfully.	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
8821a2f4-4444-4180-8da6-9dde4b6cff36	c5cac33e-d683-42e5-a870-f56bd795e9d7	96	We may terminate an employee either for cause or without cause. \n■ For cause termination is justified when an employee breaches their contract, \nengages in illegal activities (e.g. embezzlement), disrupts our workplace (e.g. \nharasses colleagues), performs below acceptable standards or causes damage \nor financial loss to our company. \n \n■ Without cause termination refers to redundancies or layoffs that may be \nnecessary if we cease some of our operations or re-assign job duties within \nteams. We will follow applicable laws regarding notice and payouts. \n \nWe will offer severance pay to eligible employees. We may also help employees who \nwere terminated without cause to find work elsewhere, if possible. \n \nWe may also compensate accrued vacation and sick leave upon termination, depending	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
1f7aa07b-68af-44f3-839d-ce339be7d2ff	c5cac33e-d683-42e5-a870-f56bd795e9d7	97	We may also compensate accrued vacation and sick leave upon termination, depending \non local law. Whenever local law doesn’t have relevant stipulations, we will pay accrued \nleave only to those who weren’t terminated for cause. We will also take into account \nunion agreements and abide by agreed terms. \n \nIf you manage team members, avoid wrongful dismissal. When you terminate an \nemployee for cause, we expect you to be certain you made the right choice and keep \naccurate performance and/or disciplinary records to support your decision. \n \nReferences \nWhen we terminate employees, we may provide references for those who leave in good \nstanding. This means that employees shouldn’t have been terminated for cause. If you \nare laid off, you may receive references. Please ask your manager.	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
b24e7faf-61fb-4626-82e8-ce083a7bc7d4	c5cac33e-d683-42e5-a870-f56bd795e9d7	98	are laid off, you may receive references. Please ask your manager. \n \nIf you resign, you may ask for references and your manager has a right to oblige or \nrefuse. \n \nPolicy revision \nWe will always strive for fairness and equal opportunity and penalize offensive and \nillegal behaviors. But, as laws and our environment change, we may revise and modify \nsome of our policies. \n \nWe have established an [annual] revision of our handbook to bring it up to date with \nlegislation and employment trends. We also ask you to contact HR if you spot any	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
35854bb2-ac0a-448a-a3d0-b1bf3b3b86c2	c5cac33e-d683-42e5-a870-f56bd795e9d7	99	inconsistencies or mistakes. And, if you have any ideas about how to improve our \nworkplace, we are happy to hear them. \n \nEmployee acknowledgement \nPlease sign to acknowledge that you’ve read this handbook and that you are committed \nto following our policies. If you need any clarifications, feel free to ask HR. \nDate: .../.../... \n………………………...	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
771df5fd-6dc3-46a2-bf51-387285ceff66	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	0	DISCIPLINARY POLICY \nArtemis | Human Resources Division \nPolicy Code: HR-DP-001 Version: 1.0 EﬀecƟve Date: April 2025 Last Reviewed: April 2025 Approved \nBy: Chief Human Resources Oﬃcer, Artemis \n \n1. PURPOSE \nThis Disciplinary Policy establishes a fair, consistent, and transparent framework for addressing \nemployee conduct and performance issues at Artemis. The objecƟve of this policy is not puniƟve in \nnature, but rather to encourage posiƟve behavioral change, maintain a respecƞul and producƟve \nwork environment, and ensure that all employees are treated equitably in disciplinary maƩers. \nArtemis is commiƩed to upholding professional standards and organizaƟonal values. This policy \nserves as a guide for managers, HR professionals, and employees to understand their rights,	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
fa100ef8-7f25-4136-b969-a8e94c2552f8	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	1	serves as a guide for managers, HR professionals, and employees to understand their rights, \nresponsibiliƟes, and the consequences of misconduct or performance deﬁciencies. \n \n2. SCOPE \nThis policy applies to: \n All full-Ɵme and part-Ɵme employees of Artemis \n Contract employees and consultants engaged on long-term assignments \n Interns and trainees working under Artemis supervision \n Employees across all departments, levels, and locaƟons \nThis policy applies to conduct occurring during working hours, on company premises, at company-\nsponsored events, or in any situaƟon where the employee is represenƟng Artemis. \n \n3. GUIDING PRINCIPLES \nArtemis adheres to the following principles in all disciplinary maƩers:	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
29cb91e4-49be-4b46-874f-2d6a212a8df1	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	2	3. GUIDING PRINCIPLES \nArtemis adheres to the following principles in all disciplinary maƩers: \n3.1 Fairness & Consistency Every disciplinary case will be handled with objecƟvity and consistency, \nirrespecƟve of the employee's designaƟon, tenure, or department. \n3.2 ProporƟonality The disciplinary acƟon taken will be proporƟonate to the severity and frequency \nof the misconduct or performance issue. \n3.3 Right to Be Heard Every employee has the right to present their side of the story before any \ndisciplinary decision is made. \n3.4 ConﬁdenƟality All disciplinary proceedings, records, and outcomes will be kept strictly \nconﬁdenƟal and shared only on a need-to-know basis. \n3.5 Non-RetaliaƟon Artemis strictly prohibits retaliaƟon against any employee who raises a concern,	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
982f3ff5-7cbd-45d5-ad34-a5728e5fd0b9	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	3	3.5 Non-RetaliaƟon Artemis strictly prohibits retaliaƟon against any employee who raises a concern, \nﬁles a complaint, or parƟcipates in a disciplinary invesƟgaƟon in good faith.	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
bc64c14d-5fe0-4c36-a521-cf3523fec8a0	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	4	3.6 DocumentaƟon All disciplinary acƟons will be formally documented and maintained in the \nemployee's personnel record. \n \n4. CATEGORIES OF MISCONDUCT \n4.1 Minor Misconduct \nMinor misconduct refers to isolated incidents of inappropriate behavior or performance lapses that \ndo not cause signiﬁcant harm but require correcƟon. Examples include: \n Occasional tardiness or unexplained absence \n Failure to meet deadlines without prior communicaƟon \n Inappropriate tone or behavior in professional communicaƟon \n Minor violaƟons of company dress code or workplace eƟqueƩe \n Unauthorized use of personal devices during work hours \n Failure to follow standard operaƟng procedures on isolated occasions \n4.2 Major Misconduct	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
fec8653e-19ed-48db-b3b8-a436c8277188	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	5	 Failure to follow standard operaƟng procedures on isolated occasions \n4.2 Major Misconduct \nMajor misconduct refers to serious breaches of conduct or repeated minor misconduct that \nsigniﬁcantly impacts the workplace, colleagues, or the organizaƟon. Examples include: \n Repeated or habitual tardiness or absenteeism \n InsubordinaƟon or deliberate refusal to follow reasonable instrucƟons \n Use of abusive, threatening, or discriminatory language \n Willful neglect of duƟes or responsibiliƟes \n Misuse of company assets, resources, or intellectual property \n Unauthorized disclosure of conﬁdenƟal or proprietary informaƟon \n FalsiﬁcaƟon of records, Ɵmesheets, or expense reports \n Bullying, harassment, or inƟmidaƟon of colleagues \n ViolaƟon of the company's IT or data security policies	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
2b5b9aa0-f965-4e7f-92d7-07b01f6f2d0d	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	6	 Bullying, harassment, or inƟmidaƟon of colleagues \n ViolaƟon of the company's IT or data security policies \n4.3 Gross Misconduct \nGross misconduct represents the most severe category of policy violaƟon and may result in \nimmediate terminaƟon without prior warnings. Examples include: \n TheŌ, fraud, or ﬁnancial dishonesty of any kind \n Physical assault or violence against any person on company premises \n Sexual harassment or any form of sexual misconduct \n Serious breach of data privacy or deliberate leakage of trade secrets	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
eebea177-2fe8-4454-a4c0-b61df4e21347	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	7	 Being under the inﬂuence of alcohol or illegal substances at the workplace \n Sabotage of company systems, data, or operaƟons \n Bribery, corrupƟon, or conﬂict of interest without disclosure \n Serious criminal conduct that impacts the company's reputaƟon or operaƟons \n FalsiﬁcaƟon of qualiﬁcaƟons, credenƟals, or idenƟty \n \n5. DISCIPLINARY PROCEDURE \nArtemis follows a structured and progressive disciplinary process designed to give employees the \nopportunity to correct their behavior before escalaƟng consequences are applied. \nStage 1 — Informal Counseling \nApplicable for: First-Ɵme minor misconduct or early-stage performance concerns \nThe immediate manager or HR representaƟve will have an informal, private conversaƟon with the \nemployee to:	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
4be8fb1b-e0d7-4119-81b4-3565e30f32bc	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	8	The immediate manager or HR representaƟve will have an informal, private conversaƟon with the \nemployee to: \n Highlight the observed behavior or performance gap \n Understand any underlying personal or professional challenges \n Agree on expected improvements and a reasonable Ɵmeline \n Oﬀer support such as mentoring, training, or workload adjustments \nOutcome: Informal counseling note maintained internally. No formal record placed in personnel ﬁle \nunless the issue recurs. \n \nStage 2 — Verbal Warning \nApplicable for: Recurring minor misconduct aŌer informal counseling, or a ﬁrst instance of moderate \nmisconduct \nA formal verbal warning will be issued by the manager, with HR present. The warning will: \n Clearly describe the speciﬁc behavior or incident	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
8b7674d7-b126-4648-99ac-91ab2eb0d408	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	9	A formal verbal warning will be issued by the manager, with HR present. The warning will: \n Clearly describe the speciﬁc behavior or incident \n Reference any prior informal counseling sessions \n State the expected behavior going forward \n Inform the employee of potenƟal consequences if behavior conƟnues \nOutcome: A wriƩen record of the verbal warning is created and retained in the employee's \npersonnel ﬁle for a period of 6 months. If no recurrence occurs, the warning is considered resolved. \n \nStage 3 — WriƩen Warning (First)	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
ff046133-6383-4c41-84a2-e859ef1d46ce	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	10	Applicable for: ConƟnued non-compliance aŌer a verbal warning, or a ﬁrst instance of major \nmisconduct \nA formal wriƩen warning leƩer will be issued, draŌed by HR and signed by the employee's \ndepartment head. The leƩer will include: \n A clear descripƟon of the violaƟon or incident \n Reference to earlier warnings or counseling \n Expected improvements and a deﬁned Performance Improvement Plan (PIP) Ɵmeline if \napplicable \n A statement of potenƟal consequences including suspension or terminaƟon \nOutcome: WriƩen warning recorded in personnel ﬁle. AcƟve for 9 months. Employee \nacknowledgment is required. \n \nStage 4 — Final WriƩen Warning \nApplicable for: Failure to meet expectaƟons set in the ﬁrst wriƩen warning, or a serious isolated \nincident of major misconduct	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
9235d165-2641-46c0-a405-e11bbf252ea4	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	11	Applicable for: Failure to meet expectaƟons set in the ﬁrst wriƩen warning, or a serious isolated \nincident of major misconduct \nA ﬁnal wriƩen warning leƩer is issued, explicitly staƟng that any further violaƟon may result in \nterminaƟon of employment. The leƩer will: \n Summarize the history of prior disciplinary acƟons \n Deﬁne speciﬁc, measurable behavioral expectaƟons \n Set a monitoring period (typically 60–90 days) \n Inform the employee of their right to appeal \nOutcome: Final wriƩen warning retained in personnel ﬁle. AcƟve for 12 months. \n \nStage 5 — Suspension (with or without pay) \nApplicable for: Pending invesƟgaƟon of serious misconduct, or as a disciplinary measure following a \nﬁnal wriƩen warning	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
ae55853e-3bd6-4308-9dcc-61f0e38331bb	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	12	Applicable for: Pending invesƟgaƟon of serious misconduct, or as a disciplinary measure following a \nﬁnal wriƩen warning \nArtemis reserves the right to place an employee on suspension during an invesƟgaƟon to: \n Protect the integrity of the invesƟgaƟon \n Ensure the safety of other employees or company assets \n Prevent potenƟal tampering with evidence or witnesses \nPaid suspension will be applied in cases where guilt has not yet been established. Unpaid \nsuspension may be applied as a formal disciplinary measure post-invesƟgaƟon for proven serious \nmisconduct. \nDuraƟon: Typically not exceeding 30 calendar days, unless extended by the Disciplinary CommiƩee.	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
20ddb083-d3a0-4305-8ecb-3284f5a56f13	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	13	Stage 6 — TerminaƟon of Employment \nApplicable for: Gross misconduct, failure to improve aŌer ﬁnal wriƩen warning, or repeated serious \nviolaƟons \nTerminaƟon will be considered aŌer: \n A formal invesƟgaƟon has been conducted \n The employee has been given an opportunity to respond \n The Disciplinary CommiƩee has reviewed the case \n HR and Legal have conﬁrmed compliance with applicable labor laws \nIn cases of gross misconduct, terminaƟon may be immediate and without prior warnings, subject to \nthe invesƟgaƟon outcome. \nOutcome: TerminaƟon leƩer issued with full & ﬁnal seƩlement processed per Artemis's SeparaƟon \nPolicy and applicable statutory requirements. \n \n6. INVESTIGATION PROCESS \n6.1 IniƟaƟon	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
c74dfaa0-dc32-41bf-beeb-356690683864	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	14	Policy and applicable statutory requirements. \n \n6. INVESTIGATION PROCESS \n6.1 IniƟaƟon \nAn invesƟgaƟon is iniƟated when a complaint is ﬁled, a manager escalates an incident, or HR \nidenƟﬁes a potenƟal breach of policy. \n6.2 Appointment of InvesƟgaƟng Oﬃcer \nHR will appoint an imparƟal InvesƟgaƟng Oﬃcer (IO), typically a senior HR professional or a neutral \ndepartment head with no conﬂict of interest in the maƩer. \n6.3 NoƟﬁcaƟon \nThe employee under invesƟgaƟon will be formally noƟﬁed in wriƟng of: \n The nature of the allegaƟon \n The commencement of the invesƟgaƟon \n Their rights during the process \n6.4 Evidence Gathering \nThe IO will gather relevant evidence including documents, emails, CCTV footage, system logs, and \nwitness statements. \n6.5 Employee Interview	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
0be76625-4340-4783-8ea7-bc927ecd4626	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	15	The IO will gather relevant evidence including documents, emails, CCTV footage, system logs, and \nwitness statements. \n6.5 Employee Interview \nThe employee will be given a formal opportunity to respond to the allegaƟons. They may be \naccompanied by a colleague or union representaƟve (where applicable) but not by an external legal \ncounsel during the interview. \n6.6 InvesƟgaƟon Report	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
1b3b5f78-cf97-4ae7-82a4-17cd4e184ab8	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	16	Upon compleƟon, the IO will submit a conﬁdenƟal invesƟgaƟon report to the Disciplinary CommiƩee \nwith ﬁndings and recommended acƟon. \n6.7 Timeline \nInvesƟgaƟons will typically be concluded within 21 working days. Complex cases may be extended \nwith wriƩen noƟﬁcaƟon to the employee. \n \n7. DISCIPLINARY COMMITTEE \nFor cases involving major misconduct, suspension, or terminaƟon, a Disciplinary CommiƩee will be \nconsƟtuted comprising: \n HR Business Partner (Chairperson) \n Department Head of the concerned employee \n Legal/Compliance RepresentaƟve (for cases involving statutory implicaƟons) \n Senior Management RepresentaƟve (for cases involving terminaƟon) \nThe commiƩee is responsible for reviewing invesƟgaƟon ﬁndings, ensuring procedural fairness, and	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
b2fec2f9-5014-4b09-ae48-f32320e2c4aa	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	17	The commiƩee is responsible for reviewing invesƟgaƟon ﬁndings, ensuring procedural fairness, and \nrecommending the appropriate disciplinary acƟon. \n \n8. EMPLOYEE RIGHTS DURING DISCIPLINARY PROCEEDINGS \nEvery employee at Artemis is enƟtled to: \n Prior noƟce of any disciplinary meeƟng or hearing \n Access to relevant documentaƟon pertaining to the allegaƟon against them \n Right to respond verbally or in wriƟng to all allegaƟons \n Accompaniment by a peer colleague or employee representaƟve during formal hearings \n Appeal rights against any disciplinary decision \n ProtecƟon from retaliaƟon for parƟcipaƟng in good faith in any proceeding \n \n9. APPEALS PROCESS \n9.1 Grounds for Appeal \nAn employee may appeal a disciplinary decision on the following grounds:	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
7e0b660c-b6cc-4ea7-a3d6-61258f45c073	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	18	9. APPEALS PROCESS \n9.1 Grounds for Appeal \nAn employee may appeal a disciplinary decision on the following grounds: \n New evidence not considered during the original invesƟgaƟon \n Procedural irregulariƟes in the disciplinary process \n DisproporƟonate or inconsistent applicaƟon of the disciplinary acƟon \n9.2 Filing an Appeal	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
fdddc7ec-0e82-4c11-aeb6-608933a0094d	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	19	The employee must submit a wriƩen appeal to the HR Division within 10 working days of receiving \nthe disciplinary decision. The appeal must clearly state the grounds and include any supporƟng \nevidence. \n9.3 Appeals CommiƩee \nA separate Appeals CommiƩee, comprising members not involved in the original decision, will review \nthe appeal. The commiƩee may: \n Uphold the original decision \n Reduce the disciplinary acƟon \n Overturn the decision enƟrely \n Order a fresh invesƟgaƟon \n9.4 Timeline \nThe Appeals CommiƩee will communicate its decision within 15 working days of receiving the \nappeal. \n9.5 Finality \nThe decision of the Appeals CommiƩee is ﬁnal and binding within the internal grievance mechanism. \nEmployees retain their rights under applicable employment law for external recourse.	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
d5b9aaae-41c2-480b-8f40-ac518af00c2e	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	20	Employees retain their rights under applicable employment law for external recourse. \n \n10. RECORD KEEPING \nDisciplinary AcƟon RetenƟon Period \nInformal Counseling Note 6 months \nVerbal Warning 6 months \nFirst WriƩen Warning 9 months \nFinal WriƩen Warning 12 months \nSuspension Record DuraƟon of employment + 3 years \nTerminaƟon Record DuraƟon of employment + 5 years \nInvesƟgaƟon Reports DuraƟon of employment + 5 years \nRecords are maintained securely by the HR Division and are accessible only to authorized personnel. \n \n11. RESPONSIBILITIES \nRole Responsibility \nEmployee Adhere to company policies; respond honestly during proceedings	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
c5e7e6de-2214-4adf-b890-85b2667a4f9e	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	21	Role Responsibility \nManager / Supervisor IdenƟfy issues early; conduct informal counseling; escalate appropriately \nHR Business Partner Guide the disciplinary process; ensure procedural compliance \nDisciplinary CommiƩee Review cases objecƟvely; recommend proporƟonate acƟon \nLegal/Compliance Ensure adherence to labor laws and statutory requirements \nSenior Management Approve terminaƟon decisions; ensure organizaƟonal consistency \n \n12. POLICY REVIEW \nThis Disciplinary Policy will be reviewed annually or as necessitated by changes in applicable labor \nlaws, organizaƟonal structure, or internal requirements. Any amendments to this policy will be \ncommunicated to all employees through oﬃcial HR channels. \n \n13. RELATED POLICIES	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
d1c5cb02-661e-44b2-b7a2-86a0fea3cb79	e719a510-1dc2-4249-a262-0fa2989cf561	22	communicated to all employees through oﬃcial HR channels. \n \n13. RELATED POLICIES \nThis policy must be read in conjuncƟon with the following Artemis policies: \n Employee Handbook \n Code of Conduct & Ethics Policy \n AnƟ-Harassment & POSH Policy \n Grievance Redressal Policy \n SeparaƟon & Exit Policy \n Data Privacy & ConﬁdenƟality Policy \n IT & Acceptable Use Policy \n Whistleblower Policy \n \n14. ACKNOWLEDGMENT \nBy conƟnuing employment at Artemis, all employees are deemed to have read, understood, and \nagreed to abide by the terms of this Disciplinary Policy. Employees are encouraged to contact the HR \nDivision for any clariﬁcaƟons.	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
7319436f-ed33-42d3-8d68-3fcdabd065b1	694562db-9c80-4fc6-9252-e6c3df7a6a7c	0	IT & INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY   |   Artemis | Information Technology & Compliance \nDivision \nPolicy Code: HR-ISP-002   |   Version: 1.0   |   Effective Date: April 2025   |   Page 1 \nIT & INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY \nArtemis | Information Technology & Compliance Division \nPolicy Code: HR-ISP-002   |   Version: 1.0   |   Effective Date: April 2025   |   Last Reviewed: April 2025   |   Approved \nBy: Chief Information Security Officer, Artemis \n1. PURPOSE \nThis IT & Information Security Policy establishes a comprehensive framework for safeguarding \nArtemis's information assets, digital infrastructure, and data systems. The objective of this policy \nis to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of all information managed by or on	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
d9b53ba5-66d4-43e3-b53f-b8615bc79cfe	694562db-9c80-4fc6-9252-e6c3df7a6a7c	1	is to protect the confidentiality, integrity, and availability of all information managed by or on \nbehalf of Artemis, and to ensure responsible use of technology resources by all personnel. \n \nArtemis is committed to maintaining a secure digital environment that supports business \ncontinuity, regulatory compliance, and the protection of employee, client, and organizational \ndata. This policy applies across all systems, networks, and devices used in connection with \nArtemis operations. \n2. SCOPE \nThis policy applies to: \n• All full-time and part-time employees of Artemis \n• Contract employees, consultants, and third-party vendors with access to Artemis \nsystems \n• Interns and trainees operating under Artemis supervision	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
ae8929dc-d66d-42e8-97d5-6aa9ad2d8f11	694562db-9c80-4fc6-9252-e6c3df7a6a7c	2	systems \n• Interns and trainees operating under Artemis supervision \n• Any individual or entity granted access to Artemis networks, systems, or data \n \nThis policy covers all IT assets including hardware, software, networks, cloud platforms, \ncommunication systems, and data repositories owned, leased, or managed by Artemis. \n3. GUIDING PRINCIPLES \nArtemis adheres to the following principles in all information security matters: \n \n3.1 Confidentiality \nInformation must be accessible only to those authorized to access it. Unauthorized disclosure or \nexposure of sensitive data is strictly prohibited. \n3.2 Integrity \nAll information and data must be accurate, complete, and protected from unauthorized \nmodification or destruction. \n3.3 Availability	\N	2026-04-10 09:48:05.090797
